      text: 'I want to pick up on something that has come up repeatedly in this discussion — the tension between what we might call the politics of recognition and the politics of redistribution. While it is true that much of third-wave and fourth-wave feminism has focused on questions of representation, visibility, and identity — who gets to be seen, whose stories get told — there is a growing concern that this focus has come at the cost of attention to the material conditions of women\'s lives: wages, reproductive healthcare, childcare infrastructure. Not only does this create a potential tension within feminist politics — it also raises the question of whether these two agendas are genuinely in tension or whether, properly understood, each requires the other. Granted that recognition matters — that symbolic representation has real material effects — it does not follow that symbolic change is sufficient in the absence of structural economic reform.',
