      text: 'The controversy over historical monuments — whether to remove statues of figures associated with colonialism or slavery — is often framed as a debate about history. But I want to suggest that it is primarily a debate about memory, and specifically about whose memory public space is designed to accommodate. Not until we recognise that monuments are not neutral historical records but active arguments about which figures deserve public honour can we have a productive debate about their future. Whereas historians tend to emphasise context and complexity — pointing out that historical figures must be judged within the frameworks of their time — advocates for removal emphasise the ongoing symbolic function of monuments in the present. For all the genuine tension between these positions, they need not be irreconcilable: one can acknowledge historical complexity while still concluding that certain figures should not be celebrated in public space.',
